Seeing their attempts at such a car/camper hybrid has had me thinking of my own version.  Leaning to a sort of, hybrid with Hammond and Clarksons.  First off for the tower, instead of a solid block of weight and air resistance utilize a collapsible square tent structure with a form of lockable scaffolding that can extend up with the tent fabric to make the second floor.  Then to prevent fall over from a stiff breeze utilize cables or ropes mounted at the top of the tent to anchor it down.  This solves a height issue but also a weight one since youâ€™re using lighter materials for the structure. So hopefully better fuel efficiency.  As for the Hybrid idea with Hammond have it possible to setup extra tent space around the main tower and vehicle in a form of U shape and have it attach to the main tower/vehicle tent.  Additionally setup this extra tent so It can detach from the main tower and vehicle, probably attached via velcro edges so you can collapse the tower and drive away for distant activities or food/supply runs.  Plus since the main tower is still part of the vehicle it grants the privacy needed for changing somewhere else.   As for why I didnâ€™t include anything of Mayâ€™s design his design. While flawed still works fairly well and is simple with room for improvement.   It was only the ambitious over engineering from the other two that inspired this form of hybrid idea.

*****Â  It has something to do with air pressure I think. What will happen is that these 2 vehicles will be pulled towards each other. If you, for example, overtake a truck and are noticeable faster then said truck, you better hold your steering wheel tight, because you can physically feel your car getting "sucked" towards that truck.

+Mike Chowtee To put it as simply as possible, as the truck moves forward it creates an area of lower pressure behind it as it displaces the air, similar to the wake of a boat. As the truck moves forward the air gets sucked back into the area where the truck used to be effectively creating a vacuum. It's also the reason why driving behind a truck is more fuel efficient and race car drivers sometimes drive directly behind their opponents (the less dense air created by the truck or car provides less resistance)
